Monokuma | Kev 2021-11-01 23:14:57Z
A large, open, campfire sits in an open patch of jungle. Coincidentally, the fireplace is situated directly in the center of all activities, being close to all the houses, kitchens, farms, and other such buildings. It seems this place was made specifically to be a hub for activities. The campfire itself is rather large and is contained with large one foot rocks. The rocks are somewhat heavy, but their main purpose is to hold the fire in. Around the campfire are benches for everyone to sit upon. The benches are simply wooden logs cut in half to have a place to sit on, but they work fine. In fact, they add to the home-like feel of the area. There are four benches in total, each on the cardinal points of the campfire, with the benches being able to hold 5 people each. On top of that, each bench has a small tent behind it, seemingly with the purpose of marking the benches. The tents are colored according to house. The house of nature has a small green tent, the house of war a red tent, the house of creation a golden yellow tent, and the house of magic has a dark blue tent. On top of that, each tent has a small flag of the colors as well. Your colors fly in the air, similarly to how the colors of the sunset adorn the sky. There's also some other utility items, such as a small bucket to hold water, and a sharpened stone axe in order to get more wood for the campfire. Ferns and flowers surround the whole area, and around those, the thick jungle.

Wynona doesn't wanna walk far, no no no! Walking takes up energy, and Wynona should save that energy for all the magic spells they're gonna cast! Well... try to cast. Wynona isn't magical. Good that the campfire was right at the centre, I guess. Wynona could look around left and right to see what's here without even moving a step. So, for now, they're just going to chill here. (edited)

Erina Normandy BOT 2021-12-04 21:32:21Z
Fear was the only word which resonated in Erina’s head. The unpleasant emotion relating to danger. It was odd how things could change in the blink of an eye. One moment, she was setting off on the boat with several others. She explored the observatory and talked to Sadao, the ultimate poet. To her, it was intriguing to her that there was at least one other ultimate besides herself on the boat. The next moment, everything began rocking and shaking, before eventually the curtains had faded to black. The feeling of dread had consumed every fiber of her in that moment, and yet she tried to remain calm. She has to always remain calm. The curtains for her had opened up once more and there she was, clothes torn lying in the sand. To her, it was a miracle she survived at all. The dread, however, still lurked behind her like a shadow. “Stay calm, stay calm.” She had to keep telling herself. “Stay calm” she told herself as the smell of blood lingered through the air at that moment. After that, however, something inside shut off. Void of all emotions, feeling nothing but the overwhelming fear. She vaguely remembered the dryad and the odd bear. He had mentioned something of a killing game, which even she didn’t really believe. Questions wandered through her head asking how did she get here, how did things escalate to the point where now she had found herself trapped within a killing game. But she was an Ultimate, and she had to show no fear.
Erina had found herself at a campfire now. Her clothes torn, her appearance disheveled. It was clear she did not stop at the dorms, or even knew of the dorms in the first place. The unfamiliar jungle surrounded her like a barricade, and the roaring fire in front of her did not help much either. She quickly took a few steps back from the fire, for it was better being safe than being burnt in the flames. Although towards anyone witnessing this, she would’ve looked childish. She took a deep breath and readjusted her posture. She tried not to think of the fire, not to think of the unknown, not to think of the very concept of the killing game she was now trapped within. She tried to fix her hair and, while it still looked a bit messy, was not as terrible as it once was. She adjusted her glasses, and noticed that she was not alone at the campfire. They seemed to just wander around the campfire, minding their own business, which might have been more of a benefit for Erina. If what Monokuma had said was true, then anyone could be viewed as a threat. Anyone could snap and kill. Or, Erina could just be using the weird bear’s words of the killing game as an extra excuse to not participate in starting a conversation.

…well, this was unexpected. Erina must’ve missed seeing Wynona when she was first walking towards the campfire. Thou’s clothes were torn as well, which could only mean that they were also on the boat and now trapped within this “killing game” Monokuma had mentioned. They seemed to be a lot more extroverted than Erina, whether for the better or for the worse. When they approached Erina, however, she flinched. How can someone be so optimistic in a place such as this? How can one be so energetic and so positive when the news of a killing game was sent out not long ago? Perhaps Erina’s sense of time was off and it had been a long while since the announcement, for she was still trying to process everything which had recently happened, but regardless, the optimism was strange in a scenario like this. The other showed no hesitation to start a conversation, calling Erina simply a “Human”. But wasn’t Wynona a human too? They surely looked to be human. Another simple question to add to her ever growing list of questions. Erina wasn’t sure how to take thee’s odd introduction. In fact, Erina was overall baffled by Wynona as a whole. But she tried to not let that confusion show. She had to be confident, and she had to not show any sort of confusion. She took a moment before she started to respond. She glanced over at the fire once more, taking a cautious step away from it. Then, she looked back over at Wynona as she confidently spoke. “Erina Normandy, Ultimate Geologist.” She responded, her tone being very assertive and to the point. “Pleasure to meet you, Wynona.” Despite how untidy Erina looked in the current moment, she still attempted to remain stern and formal. First impressions are always the most important when meeting someone new, after all. And for Erina, every first impression had to be on her best foot forward, even if she was truly feeling at her worst.

Erina was always one who stated her ultimate with every introduction. The title “Ultimate Geologist” was something she has always taken great pride in ever since earning that title. She also believes it helps her appear more professional at a first encounter, for not everyone is lucky enough to be considered an ultimate. It is called an ultimate for a reason after all; only the best truly deserve the title. Only the best are worthy of being considered an ultimate. She didn’t take too much notice towards Wynona’s embarrassment, surprisingly. Erina was one who kept a more formal posture, so it would make complete sense for them to be slightly intimidated by the geologist. Regardless, she listened to Wynona briefly explain thee’s ultimate talent, which revolves around science as well, specifically clouds. Well, it is not everyday you meet another ultimate, especially one which resides within the sciences. “So you are an ultimate as well, I see.” She started. “Some we both have in common, it seems. Talents which reside within the more natural side of science.” She responded. Erina heard Wynona respond to the greeting and watched them hold out thou’s hand for a handshake. She looked at thee’s hand, and then accepted the handshake. It was the proper thing to do, after all. After the handshake was all said and done, though, Erina once again glanced over at the fire once again. She snapped back once again towards the conversation. Ever since the shipwreck, Erina had noticed she had slipped into her inner fears more and more. Even the simplest of things had begun to put her on edge. Although perhaps trying to continue the conversation could benefit Erina in the sense of being able to distract herself from the fears of the killing game. It was a common habit for someone, after all. Distracting oneself from a larger and more painful thought.
“Although Regarding your talent, what does Nephology all entail? Do you work more regarding cloud movement patterns, or is it more of simply classifying clouds?” She questioned thee. Despite how she may act, Erina had always been one who wished to learn more. She is always one to ask questions, although she would also try to answer as many of her own questions as she could on her own as well. While asking the question, while she still kept her formal tone, she seemed to almost relax herself a bit, showing a more genuine curiosity within this field of study. Day after day after day, she had worked hard within her field of study, so hearing from another ultimate working in the field of sciences may be a bit beneficial to her. Surely the discussion of their talents would bring some sort of interesting topics towards the conversation. Alongside that, Erina would wish for a conversation like this over talking about the killing game any day of the week.

It always comes back to ultimates. Of course that sort of topic would be brought up in a scenario like this. A jungle in the middle of who knows where in which several ultimates of various titles now reside, trapped within this unfamiliar world of the killing game. Whether it was magic which started this game, or perhaps a more logical reason, that really did not matter. Those seeds of death had since been planted in the grounds of this killing game, and with time the vines of despair will begin to wrap around each participating student. It seemed that whatever nervousness Wynona once had simply vanished, as if there was never any fear to begin with. Erina listened to Wynona begin their explanation on what their ultimate entails. Thou’s response was a bit vague, only briefly mentioning something of a cloud witch. What even was a cloud witch? To Erina, the concept of “the cloud witch” seemed a little far fetched. At the same time, however, ever since first boarding the boat, nothing truly had made sense. How would one logically explain there is a monochromatic bear in the middle of the jungle who kidnapped several ultimates to participate in a death game? How would one explain the fact they got attacked by a dryad in a cave. If she were to ask these questions aloud, most would tell her she probably had some sort of bad dream, or everything she was stating was being made up. This entire experience could not be logically explained, which tore straight into the logical thinker. She was continuously attempting to grasp for answers with the smallest details, but in the end she would be led nowhere. She would be right back in the position of being trapped in the unknown, in the unexplained, with no hope of getting answers.
So, she thought of the logical side. They were trapped in a jungle with no way of escape. But, at least there was someone else here. At least she was not stranded alone, with no hope for survival. There was the killing game, which only helped throw more of the students into a state of fear. Erina turned around briefly at the jungle which surrounded the general area. The dark unknown of the dense forest surrounded them, and the bonfire in front of her did not help to illuminate the dark forest. For a brief moment, there was a wave of uncertainty from the geologist. But, it was quickly wiped away as she adjusted her glasses, ready to ask more questions. “Who is this ‘Cloud Witch’ you have mentioned? What role does she play within your own studies?” She questioned, trying to avoid thinking of the current situation. Under a normal circumstance, she would have pushed aside the idea of a “cloud witch”. However, anything would be better than a discussion about the killing game, even if it is a little absurd.

One two three four. Pictures of 7 different people flashed upon screen. A lot of them were doing their own things, being their own people. If it weren't for the motive, nobody would have probably guessed they were even related in the first place. A mother and a father, in their own house. Although they both held quite a melancholic aura. An oldest sibling. Working at some nondescript hair salon and talking with customers. An older sister. A woman designing a house. These pictures on their own were enough to make October uneasy, but then more flashed on the screen. Five and Six. A younger sibling, quietly running through the woods. And a youngest sibling, standing guard. Apparently. In a strange, sewer like area. He seemed bored, Leaning up against the wall. A sight enough to make October's blood run cold. Her eyes widened, all words in her throat getting stuck. Had all those years of hide and seek been worthless? If they had found it- No, they couldn't have. There was no way. After what everyone had been through, why would it all be a waste now? ...Seven. Just a feed of a tall blue haired kid, presumably around October's age. He was in a very dark room, which was filled with stacks of books and blankets and that sort of stuff. He was sitting there and talking to some other person, who was offscreen. But something as simple as this was enough to bring tears to October's eyes. No. No. This couldn't be. "No I-" October couldn't even choke out any words as tears bubbled up in the corners of her eyes. She was so distressed by such a simple thing, it was almost disturbing. Just a feed of someone she loved- What was so bad about that? Well, maybe if he hadn't been missing for two years, it probably wouldn't be so bad. If many people had not died because of the whole domino effect of events he was part of, then it wouldn't have stung so bad. If October couldn't even get up and go see him without having to relive one of the worst days of her life,
it probably wouldn't be too painful. These videos were just salt in the gaping wounds that October had been hiding for years. She was brought to nothing more than a sobbing mess. So much for Connect 4.
